# Ops/PII database split

Two separate Postgres databases, two separate Prisma schemas:

- `prisma/schema.prisma` → ops DB, client `src/lib/prisma.ts` (`prisma`). Auth (`User`/`Session`/`Account`/`Verification`), `Division`, memberships, invitations. No Field Ops models yet (jobs/tickets rebuilt later).
- `prisma/pii/schema.prisma` → PII DB, client `src/lib/prisma-pii.ts` (`prismaPii`, a lazily-connected proxy). Owns lead ingest: `Division` (replicated), `Lead`, `Activity`, `IngestKey`. CRM `Customer` / `Contact` / `ServiceLocation` are deferred.

**Never add a PII-identity column (name, email, phone, street address) to the ops schema.** This is enforced by `src/features/accounting/ops-pii-schema-guard.test.ts` (`npm run test:schema-guard`) — run it after touching either schema. When ops rows later need customer display data, join in application code against `prismaPii` (batch fetch + merge). There is no cross-database Prisma relation; don't try to model one.

The PII DB is not guaranteed to be configured in every environment (Vercel `CLIENT_DB_SECRET_ARN` wiring is still pending — see the header comment in `prisma-pii.ts`). Always check `isPiiConfigured()` before relying on `prismaPii`, and degrade gracefully (e.g. lead ingest returns `503` / `pii_unconfigured`) — match that pattern in new code instead of letting a missing config crash the page.

Two schemas mean two of most commands: `db:generate` + `db:generate:pii`, `db:migrate` + `db:migrate:pii`. Run `sync:divisions-pii` after an ops migration touches `Division` rows, to keep the two databases' division tables aligned.
